addr="nt-001K"
title="A point whose coordinates like in a quadratic extension of the field is directly constructible">each directly constructible point gives us a quadratic field extension</fr:link>, the forward proof is obvious.</fr:p>
<fr:p><fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(\Longleftarrow )]]></fr:tex> Suffices to show <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\sqrt {\ell }]]></fr:tex> is constructible, but this is the well-known construction using the "geometric mean theorem". Given a length <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\ell ]]></fr:tex>, we draw a line <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[PQ]]></fr:tex> passing through <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex> and {Q} and find the intersection <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[P']]></fr:tex> of the circle centered at <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex> of length <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\ell ]]></fr:tex> with the line <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[PQ]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[|P'Q|=\ell +1]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
<fr:p>Now, we find the midpoint between <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[P']]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[Q]]></fr:tex> and call this <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex> (for "midpoint"). We draw a circle <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[C(M,Q)]]></fr:tex> centered at <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex> passing through <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[Q]]></fr:tex> (and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[P']]></fr:tex>). We draw a perpendicular line with <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[PQ]]></fr:tex> passing through <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex> which intersects <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[C(M,Q)]]></fr:tex> at <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[Q']]></fr:tex>. Then the length of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[|PQ'|=\sqrt {\ell }]]></fr:tex> by the well-known geometric mean theorem. Hence the result.</fr:p><html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
class="qed">∎</html:span></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter><fr:tree
